{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe compaction fold claims an all-or-none contract (invariant I1): snapshot written\nfirst, sources renamed to `*.retired`, and on failure every completed rename reversed\nand the snapshot removed. But in `src/rebar/_commands/compact.py` (~lines 235-247) the\nrollback path only *logs* a failed reverse-rename and continues, then unconditionally\nremoves the snapshot and returns failure. Because normal replay excludes `*.retired`\n(`src/rebar/reducer/_cache.py`), a source that failed to restore becomes invisible with\nno snapshot left to carry its folded effect — silent, undetectable data loss that\nviolates the stated contract.\n\n## What\n\nChosen approach (committed — not \"retain OR sentinel\"): **retain the snapshot.** The\nsnapshot already carries the folded effect of every source, so keeping it is the minimal\nchange and needs no new on-disk artifact. On any reverse-rename failure during rollback,\nskip the `os.remove(snapshot)` step, emit an explicit `rollback incomplete; run fsck`\ndiagnostic, and return failure.\n\nKey realization from the fsck code: with the snapshot retained, the residual mixed state\nis **already detectable and repairable by existing fsck** — no new issue kind is needed:\n- A source that WAS reversed back to an active `.json` is a UUID in the snapshot's\n  `source_event_uuids` whose active file \"still exists\" → the existing\n  `SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT` check (`src/rebar/_commands/fsck.py:302`) fires, and it is\n  already in the `--repair-snapshots` rebuild trigger (`fsck.py:191`).\n- A source that failed to reverse stays `*.retired` and folded in the snapshot — i.e. the\n  normal healthy compacted state; no false positive (crucially, this means the detection\n  does NOT fire on healthy fully-compacted tickets).\nSo this story's only production change is: **do not delete the snapshot** in the\nrollback-failure branch (plus the diagnostic). The existing `SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT` +\n`--repair-snapshots` path already reconciles the mixed state (confirmed against\n`fsck.py`), so **no fsck code change is expected**.\n\nTwo correctness notes folded in from review:\n- **Repair mechanism is retire, not rebuild.** `_repair_ticket`'s `SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT`\n  branch reconciles by **retiring** the still-active source (renaming it to `*.retired`),\n  not by writing a new snapshot — so the test must assert the formerly-active source now\n  carries `.retired` and a follow-up `fsck` exits 0, NOT that a rebuild commit occurred.\n- **Read-safety during the mixed window.** Between the rollback failure and a\n  `fsck --repair-snapshots`, a reversed-to-active source is both live AND folded in the\n  retained snapshot, so a naive replay could double-count it. The `rollback incomplete`\n  diagnostic must therefore WARN that normal reads are unsafe until repair; the story\n  confirms whether replay already refuses/repairs an inconsistent snapshot or documents\n  the window as read-unsafe.\n- **Durability of the decision.** Add an architectural comment at the retained-snapshot\n  branch in `compact.py` explaining WHY the snapshot is intentionally not removed (so a\n  future refactor doesn't \"fix\" it back into the data-loss hazard), and note the\n  compact→fsck recovery contract in the concurrency docs.\n\n- Add fault-injection tests (currently the negative suite injects only at\n  `compact.lock.acquire` and `compact._git`, never in the rename loop).\n\n## Scope\n\n- `src/rebar/_commands/compact.py` (rollback-failure branch: retain snapshot + diagnostic)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/fsck.py` (verify the existing `_check_snapshot`/`_scan` +\n  `--repair-snapshots` rebuild covers the mixed state; extend only if a gap is found)\n- `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_compact_negative.py` (new fault-injection tests)\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Forward-rename fault test: inject `OSError` on the 2nd/3rd forward `os.rename`;\n      assert nonzero exit, no active snapshot, every original filename restored, no\n      stray `*.retired`, reduced state deep-equal to pre-compaction, clean `fsck`, and\n      an idempotent re-compaction.\n- [ ] Reverse-rename fault test: inject a forward failure AND a reverse-rename failure\n      (so at least one source is reversed-to-active and at least one stays `*.retired`);\n      assert the snapshot is NOT deleted, a recoverable diagnostic is emitted, and no\n      source data is lost.\n- [ ] The `rollback incomplete` diagnostic warns that normal reads are unsafe until\n      `fsck --repair-snapshots` runs.\n- [ ] `fsck` (no flag) reports `SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT` for the reversed-to-active\n      source in that mixed state (existing detection), and does NOT flag a healthy\n      fully-compacted ticket.\n- [ ] `fsck --repair-snapshots` reconciles by RETIRING the still-active source (asserts\n      it now carries `.retired`, no new snapshot written); a follow-up `fsck` exits 0 and\n      the reducer's event-UUID set + payloads deep-equal the set recorded in the retained\n      snapshot's `source_event_uuids`.\n- [ ] An architectural comment in `compact.py` documents why the snapshot is retained on\n      rollback failure, and the compact→fsck recovery contract is noted in\n      `docs/concurrency.md`.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783891274378529001,"uuid":"6314f79d-b371-4da7-b911-3afabe54d640"}